  "short": {
    "headline": "Data gap: We know the rate but not the exact number of child deaths",
    "dek": "India's under-five mortality rate has fallen sharply, but without live birth figures, we cannot give a precise count of deaths.",
    "body": "The evidence provides only the under-five mortality rate (U5MR) — the number of deaths per 1,000 live births. The latest available rate is 26.6 per 1,000 live births (World Bank, 2024), down from 241.3 in 1960. However, to answer 'how many children die' in absolute terms, we also need the number of live births in India. That data is not included in the provided sources. Therefore, while we can describe the trend in the rate, we cannot calculate the exact number of child deaths."
  },
  "article": {
    "title": "How Many Indian Children Die Before Age Five? The Data Gap",
    "standfirst": "India's under-five mortality rate has dropped to around 27 per 1,000 live births, but converting that to a count of deaths requires live birth data that is not in the evidence packet.",
    "bodyMarkdown": "The question asks for the number of Indian children who die before reaching age five. The available evidence, however, reports only the under-five mortality rate (U5MR) — the probability of dying before age five per 1,000 live births. It does not include the total number of live births in India, which is necessary to convert the rate into an absolute count of deaths.\n\n**What the data says**\n\nThree sources provide U5MR estimates for India:\n\n- **World Bank (2024)**: 26.6 per 1,000 live births, the latest observation in a series that began at 241.3 in 1960.\n- **WHO Global Health Observatory (2023)**: 27.8 per 1,000 live births (both sexes, all wealth quintiles), with a 95% uncertainty interval of 23.9–32.1.\n- **UN Population Division (2020)**: projections for 2030 give 22.3 per 1,000 live births (median, both sexes). Historical estimates for 2000 were 91.1 per 1,000 live births.\n\nAll sources show a steep decline in the U5MR over the past six decades. In 1960, the rate was 241.3; by 2023–2024 it had fallen to around 27. The decline is consistent across sexes: WHO estimates for 2023 give 27.8 for females and 27.7 for males. The WHO data also reveals striking inequality: among the poorest wealth quintile the rate was 42.2 in 2023, compared to 14.3 among the richest.\n\n**Why we cannot answer the question**\n\nThe question requires an absolute number of deaths. For that, we need the number of live births in India for the same year. For example, if we had 25 million live births in 2024, a U5MR of 26.6 would imply about 665,000 deaths. But the evidence does not contain any live birth figures. Without them, any number we might calculate would be purely speculative.\n\n**What the data does not say**\n\nThe evidence does not include official Indian statistics. WHO notes that its estimates are not the official statistics of India, which come from the Sample Registration System (SRS) of the Office of the Registrar General. The SRS data is not present in this packet.\n\nAlso, the U5MR is a probability, not a count. It cannot be summed across years or regions without full demographic data. The packet contains only national-level aggregates, so regional or state-level child deaths cannot be derived.\n\n**Conclusion**\n\nTo properly answer 'how many Indian children die before age five', one needs both the under-five mortality rate and the number of live births. Since the latter is missing from the evidence, the question cannot be answered with the available data. Future updates should include live birth counts or direct estimates of child deaths.\n\n**Sources used**\n\n- World Bank: Under-five mortality rate, 2024 (26.6 per 1,000 live births) and 1960 (241.3).\n- WHO Global Health Observatory: Under-five mortality rate, 2023 (27.8 per 1,000 live births, both sexes, total wealth).\n- UN Population Division: Under-five mortality rate projections for 2030 (22.3 per 1,000 live births) and historical estimate for 2000 (91.1)."
  },
